For classes such as `javax.activation.DataSource` you need the JAR file for the JavaBeans Activation Framework.

You can download the JAR from Maven Central [here](https://mvnrepository.com/artifact/javax.activation/activation/1.1.1) - click on the `jar` link there.

If you are using a dependency management tool such as Maven, Gradle, etc. then use the related configuration (also available in that same page). Using a dependency management tool is **strongly recommended** over just downloading JAR files one-by-one.

---

You should also consider replacing your `javax` imports with `jakarta` imports, since that is now [where these packages are maintained](https://blogs.oracle.com/javamagazine/post/transition-from-java-ee-to-jakarta-ee), going forward.

If you do that, then you need to use the Jakarta Activation API, available [here](https://mvnrepository.com/artifact/jakarta.activation/jakarta.activation-api). For example:

```xml
&lt;dependency&gt;
    &lt;groupId&gt;jakarta.activation&lt;/groupId&gt;
    &lt;artifactId&gt;jakarta.activation-api&lt;/artifactId&gt;
    &lt;version&gt;2.0.1&lt;/version&gt;
&lt;/dependency&gt;
```

And if you do that, you should also replace JavaMail classes too - for example, you can replace this:

```java
import javax.mail.Message;
```

with this:

```java
import jakarta.mail.Message;
```

And use a [Jakarta Mail](https://mvnrepository.com/artifact/com.sun.mail/jakarta.mail) resource, for example:

```xml
&lt;dependency&gt;
    &lt;groupId&gt;com.sun.mail&lt;/groupId&gt;
    &lt;artifactId&gt;jakarta.mail&lt;/artifactId&gt;
    &lt;version&gt;2.0.1&lt;/version&gt;
&lt;/dependency&gt;
```

```
return this.executor.schedule(
   () -&gt; {
      try {
         LOG.info(&quot;before run&quot;);
         task.run();
      } finally {
         semaphore.release();
      }
    },
    delay,
